Been there, I'm 26 now and get to dress however I want. But from my experience, it seems like your mom has good values. I don't think it's right for young girls to wear "revealing" clothes, something I didn't realize till I gained some more experience in life. That doesn't mean that you can't wear a crop top and make it not revealing, I have a rule that if my top is more risky I wear high-waisted or more covering bottoms and vice versa. Also I don't know if you have this kind of relationship, but you should try talking to your mom about this as you get older and make it clear to her that you have a passion for outward expression and style more as your getting older and that it would mean a lot to you if you two could explore and meet halfway on certain trends or styles you're into. Honestly wish I had tried that with my mom, could've saved me years of fashion mistakes â¤   Worst case scenario your stuck in the same position till you're old enough...Best case scenario it could be a great way to bond with your mom instead of that all too familiar frustrated/almost embarrassed feeling when clothing shopping with a parent.

Basically what I started doing was making my mom shop with me (like right next to me holding the shopping cart) so that she could see everything Iâ€™m picking out and can give her opinion. Comment includes a list of basics u should buy so keep reading!!! for those complaining about not having enough clothes i was definitely there with you but over the year iâ€™ve slowly built my closet up from thrifting and iâ€™d like to compile a list of clothes you should get first: -mom jeans or more loose fitting jeans sort of a rare find but if ur on the smaller side check the kids section. get a light wash and black one -skinny jeans make sure EVERY jean u get is high waisted. -fitted t-shirtâ€™s (black, white, creme, colored) - loose graphic tees (u can find these in abundance) -black denim and light wash denim jackets very important and you can save up and buy new bc i wear them on the daily -cardigans or zipups in simple colors.  -white and black sneakers -black joggers (tapered to the bottom) -black and white turtle necks  - hoodies for casual days  these clothes are all VERY easy to mix and match so you can look like you have more clothes than you actually do and A LOT of them are easy to find at the thrift store others you might have to but new.   donâ€™t be scared about how long the list looks bc you can take your time building it up and depending in your situation it might be easier to build up than you especially if youâ€™re thrifting these.    items to get after you accumulated the basics: -cool pants (plaid pants, striped pants, flowy are pants) that arenâ€™t too bold. they can have color but they shouldnâ€™t be too bright) same goes for cooler shirts (the cut of the shirt and pants matter too - accessories (chains, belts, cross body bags, side bags, fanny packs, and jewelry)  - more sneakers (u can easily thrift converse) or heels (also easy to thrift) -and whatever you think is fashionable because overtime you do develop a sense of fashion -dresses (not very practical so thts why itâ€™s on this section bc you shouldnâ€™t be buying dresses when you first build ur closet unless itâ€™s absolutely perfect) -skirts   i donâ€™t want to come off like i think iâ€™m a pro. this is from personal experience and tips i wouldâ€™ve loved when i started first buying clothes. i only bought colorful and trendy stuff and i thought iâ€™d get a lot of wear out of them but i didnâ€™t. BUY BASICS and timeless pieces that can last a long time and match with everything before getting in with statements pieces.   and these should looks good on all body types and you can always buy something else over something i recommend if it caters to your body better. and to the ppl tht feel ugly trust me dressing up does A LOT for you. ur hair also matters btw. so dress for urself and feel more confident.   another tip coming from a short person tht EVERYONE should do is to tuck in their shirts because that makes u looks more put together. adding accessories also makes u look more fashionable like ashleyâ€™s first example of changing up jeans and t-shirt.

I used to have the same problem but not anymore when I realized that I couldn't change my community but I definitely didn't want to be boring for my whole life. What makes you uncomfortable the most is actually your inside thoughts and believe me, that was my biggest problem. But the more you dress the way you want, you will eventually not care about people anymore because wearing what you like actually makes you feel so good that you can have enough energy for the whole day.  You can start with something minor that people only notice when they look carefully or they will forget after 5 minutes like wearing tops that are just a little brighter than the colors you usually wear with your normal pans or wearing dresses that have interesting styles but in neutral colors, so people won't notice that much even though they can feel something new but are not bothered enough to say anything, but the most important thing is that you feel better wearing something you actually like without attracting attention. And I can tell you, that feeling is so addictive that you will gradually not care about what people think anymore and wear whatever you want. This process don't usually take that long haha, what you change here is not people's attitude but actually your mind, making you feel more self-confident about yourself. Like I said, ask yourself this question: Do you want to be boring your whole life because of other people who do not live your life for you?

A lot of people are stressin' in the comments because they have no good clothes. Let me tell you something - Ross is a very good place to go if you don't like thrift stores. I wanted to "up my outfit game" so I tried Ross because my sister suggested we go. It's a hit or miss store which kind of sucks, but it's always worth the shot. The clothes range from like $3-$15 usually which is pretty good.  But if you still think that's a lot, try out a thrift store. Many people go to Goodwill, but I personally prefer a Salvation Army thrift store. I actually went yesterday and got 1 skirt, 7 shirts, 1 dress, and 1 sweater all for $34! My go-to place before thrift stores or Ross was Kohl's, but for $34 I could literally buy like 2 graphic tees there. It may not be your ideal option, but I was pretty against it myself until I saw the range of things I could get. Give it a shot, you may be pleasantly surprised.   For a few tips, here are some of my suggestions:   -If you have some old shirts you don't usually wear, try looking up some shirt cutting tutorials. I personally don't like to cut up my old shirts, but I did buy a plain blue shirt from the thrift store and I cut off the entire neckline so it was off the shoulder and when paired with a black skirt... dang it looks good.  -In general, try to repurpose old clothes. If you don't like a pair of jeans, cut them up!  -Many shirts (if they seem boring) can easily be paired with a black skirt or jeans if you tuck it in. I use this a lot and I love it. -If you have shirts you don't like because they are too long, crop them. If I do this, I'll usually also cut the sleeves and collar so it looks more "natural" -Encourage yourself to go through your closet. If you find clothes you don't wear often, donate them. A lot of people keep clothes they don't wear (I'm super guilty about this) and it takes up space. You either just don't like them or honestly forgot about them. Regardless, if you clear up some space you may discover what you're looking for and it may help you realize what kinds of clothes you want! -Walmart has some pretty interesting shoe options. I got a cute pair of sneakers once. If you're in need of some new shoes, try to look for some there.   And for my final tip, DO NOT buy clothes you feel pressured to wear. I was a very self-conscious middle schooler and many of my old shirts and shorts are much longer than I'd wear now just so I could cover myself up. As I got into maybe 7th grade, I bought a couple really short-shorts and a crop top I wore once. I was a chubby kid and I still am. I did not like my style, but I didn't like to show off my body. I now wear these items because they're more appropriate at my age, but don't make yourself uncomfortable. I still find days where crop tops I love just don't suit my stomach AND THAT'S OKAY! Just wear clothes you like, not for anyone else. You'll save money and all around just be happier.    I hope this helps someone out there :)

Hi love I actually do exactly everything that Ashley does currently since high school (im 23 now) LOL. I am 5'1'. And all these have saved my life when I was super broke before and even now (thrifting to regular shopping). I found that when wearing these types of outfits, a lot of the focus has to do with your waist and the length of the skirts and pants and how much skin should or shouldn't be showing.  I found shorter skirts make my legs look a lot longer. I cuff my pants slightly above my ankles (and it's a lot more flattering when it's tapered). I love how Ashley gave those belt ideas because that's how I always do my cheap hems. Belts save lives (almost ALL of my belts are thrifted, I also bought a belt hole puncher to make the belt tighter).  Another tip I got from one of my model friends (she's fkin like 5'9' tho so it's not like she needs these tips LMFAO) was that you should wear strapless heels/sandals during the summer because apparently it makes you look a lot taller? I don't really notice much of a difference but that's what her agency tells her.  My hair is also incredibly long so a certain amount of hair length also helps you look taller too from what I noticed, since my hair is super long now (past my butt) it makes me look much shorter since my hair makes me look a bit boxy sometimes.  And lastly (from what I can think of), ANGLES. Ashley always has her camera pointed up from wherever she is filming. I ALWAYS take pictures/videos of myself with the camera slightly angled up towards me and this makes you look more elongated.  Hope these help ~

N M Taylor Iâ€™m no fashion youtubers but I have a few tips! 1) try wearing a more winter-y skirt with black tights while itâ€™s colder outside. Thick tights donâ€™t show much skin at all, and that way you can get used to wearing skirts! 2) little shorts are often in the lingerie section of stores and theyâ€™re often called spandex. But I personally would recommend going to a store that sells sports equipment/clothing! Athletes wear spandex shorts under their uniforms, and in my opinion those ones donâ€™t slide around as much as the lingerie ones do :)

I'm also not a fashion expert, but I (almost) always end up wearing bike shorts under my skirts/dresses. They hug your body very tightly so there is hardly ever a seam line noticeable on the skirt unless you wear a bodycon skirt/dress. It gives me more confidence while wearing them since I don't have to worry about accidentally flashing anyone! i also use plain tights or leggings under them. Thin ones with patterns or designs sometimes catch people's eye more than I like, so plain ones (even thin ones!) typically aren't too noticeable to gross men, unless they're really perving on you.  I don't have much advice for getting over that mindset, since there is nothing wrong with wanting to cover up if it makes you more comfortable. But if you want to try it out, get used to wearing shorter skirts around your house first, dance around in them, and realize how cute you look! Hang out with girl friends who will support you and make you feel confident while you're out (:
